\begin_layout Standard
There are three parties involved in the search and matching process: sellers,
 buyers and the platform itself.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is mass 1 of sellers, who always stay on the platform, never leave
 or arrive.
 The sellers are passive searchers; they do not actively look for jobs,
 but instead are presented with a sequence of job offers at Poisson rate,
 and decide whether to accept or reject them to maximize discounted profit
 flow.
 An accepted job takes time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to complete, during which time the seller cannot receive new jobs.
 This is the search friction.
 At each moment in time, there are two pools of sellers: available and busy.
 Available sellers wait for jobs, busy sellers work on their job.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a continuum of potential buyers who gradually arrive over time
 at flow rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, within an time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

, mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta dt$
\end_inset

 of buyers arrive to the platform.
 Buyers are short lived.
 Buyer search is passive: they put up a job and the platform assigns them
 to an available seller.
 If their job is accepted, they stay until the job is completed, otherwise
 they leave.
